CapitalQuant Development Methodology
Complete Workflow
Your methodology flows from why (conceptual) → what (design) → how (implementation) in six distinct phases.
________________________________________
Phase 0: Conceptual Foundation
Purpose: Establish the investment thesis, product vision, business rationale, and strategic positioning before any design or implementation.
Documents (already complete):
#	Document	Question It Answers
01	Product Concept	Why does this platform need to exist? What problem does it solve?
02	Business Context	Why is explainable investment intelligence necessary?
03	Machine Learning Strategy	Why XGBoost? Why supervised learning?
04	Explainability Strategy	Why SHAP? How will predictions be interpreted?
05	Document Intelligence Strategy	Why RAG? Why SEC filings?
06	Technical Roadmap	How will the platform be built incrementally?
Gate condition: Product concept reviewed and approved.
Output: Confidence that the product vision is technically and commercially sound before engineering begins.
________________________________________
Phase 1: High-Level Design (HLD)
Purpose: Translate the product concept into a complete software architecture. Define layers, services, data flows, and technology choices without implementation details.
Documents:
•	docs/hld/system_architecture.md
•	docs/hld/product_architecture.md
•	docs/hld/dashboard_design.md
Key decisions made here:
•	Modular AI architecture
•	ETL pipeline
•	Predictive engine
•	Explainability engine
•	Document Intelligence (RAG)
•	FastAPI backend
•	React dashboard
•	MLflow experiment tracking
Gate condition: Architecture reviewed, dependencies identified, technology stack approved.
Output: Complete system architecture with clearly defined components.
________________________________________
Phase 2: Low-Level Design (LLD)
Purpose: Define the implementation details of every module, including APIs, schemas, pipelines, models, and interfaces.
Documents (one per component):
•	docs/lld/etl_pipeline.md
•	docs/lld/feature_engineering.md
•	docs/lld/xgboost_model.md
•	docs/lld/shap_engine.md
•	docs/lld/rag_pipeline.md
•	docs/lld/api_design.md
•	docs/lld/dashboard.md
Each LLD includes:
•	Function signatures
•	Expected inputs and outputs
•	Data schemas
•	Error handling
•	API contracts
•	Testing requirements
•	Dependencies
Gate condition: All implementation details reviewed and unambiguous.
Output: Technical specifications that can be implemented without additional design decisions.
________________________________________
Phase 3: Production Specification
Purpose: Produce a single master specification that consolidates the HLD and LLD into one executable reference document.
Document:
docs/specs/capitalquant_production_spec.md
What it contains:
•	Executive summary
•	Overall architecture
•	Complete data flow
•	Layer-by-layer specifications
•	Technology stack
•	Acceptance criteria
•	Success metrics
Why this exists: The production specification becomes the single source of truth and prevents inconsistencies between design documents.
Gate condition: Specification frozen before implementation begins.
Output: Unified implementation contract.
________________________________________
Phase 4: Prompt Generation
Purpose: Transform the production specification into implementation prompts for each independent module.
Documents:
docs/prompts/prompt_01.md
docs/prompts/prompt_02.md
...
Prompt structure:
Section	Content
Overview	Purpose of the module
Inputs	Expected data and interfaces
Outputs	Return values and artifacts
Error Handling	Failure scenarios
API	Interface specification
Tests	Validation criteria
Example	Expected behavior
Gate condition: Prompts reviewed and ready for implementation.
Output: Self-contained implementation prompts.
________________________________________
Phase 5: Implementation
Purpose: Build the platform incrementally following the production specification.
Implementation order:
1.	ETL Pipeline
2.	Feature Engineering
3.	XGBoost Model
4.	SHAP Explainability
5.	FastAPI Backend
6.	RAG Pipeline
7.	React Dashboard
8.	Docker & Deployment
Process for each module:
1.	Execute implementation prompt
2.	Develop module
3.	Run tests
4.	Commit changes
5.	Continue to the next module
Gate condition: Tests pass and integration succeeds.
Output: Working production-ready software.
________________________________________
Phase 6: Validation
Purpose: Verify that every component satisfies the functional and quantitative objectives defined during the conceptual phase.
Validation activities:
Predictive Model
•	Walk-forward validation
•	ROC AUC
•	Precision
•	Recall
•	Accuracy
•	Calibration Curve
•	Confusion Matrix
•	Global SHAP
•	Local SHAP
RAG System
•	Precision@5
•	Recall@5
•	Faithfulness
•	Context Precision
Product Validation
•	Dashboard functionality
•	API integration
•	Explainability verification
•	Document retrieval verification
Gate condition: All validation metrics satisfy project requirements.
Output: Validation report and production-ready platform.
